
HTMLESCAPE(3)            BSD Library Functions Manual            HTMLESCAPE(3)

NNAAMMEE
     hhttmmlleessccaappee -- HTML escape the characters '<', '>', '&' and '"'

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
     ##iinncclluuddee <<hhttmmlleessccaappee..hh>>

     _i_n_t
     hhttmmlleessccaappee(_c_o_n_s_t _c_h_a_r _*_s_r_c, _c_h_a_r _*_*_d_s_t);

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
     The hhttmmlleessccaappee function parses a  string and converts the characters
     listed above to their corresponding HTML entities.

     The calling program is responsible for freeing the memory allocated to
     _*_d_s_t_.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
     hhttmmlleessccaappee returns 0 on success.  If memory could not be allocated for
     the destination string, then ENOMEM is returned.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEE
     The following code fragment illustrates a simple usage:

           char *dst = 0;

           htmlescape("forbidden: < > & \
           printf("dst = '%s'0, dst);
           free(dst);

     produces this output:

           dst = 'forbidden: &lt; &gt; &amp; &quote;'

